Yes, data components should only deal with data - fetch/prepare/broadcast.

here is what I would do (which is similar to what you described):
- compile and dump your templates as json string in a file (templateName - template pairs)
- make those templates global or pass them to the page (eg. app/page/default.js) when you boot/initialize it (on app/main.js)
- create a mixin that you can use with UI components. It exposes a render method/interface to the template engine
- when you attach the UI component to DOM elements you pass a template from the `templates` object like this 

``` javascript
Foo.attachTo(document.body, {
    fooTpl: templates.foo
});
```
- that you can render later

``` javascript
this.dataReceived = function (event, data) {
    var tpl = this.render(this.attr.fooTpl, data);
    this.$node.append(tpl);
};
```

If you want to decouple you could create a UI component that would act as renderer (like a network printer). It would hold all the tempaltes and any UI component could ask it to render a `templateName` with some `data`. Here you'd have to deal with the event ownership issue. Also the UI component should know the `templateName` in advance.
Overall the latter adds more complexity and I am not sure whether it is an optimal solution.

